169. Majority Element
Given an array nums of size n, return the majority element.
The majority element is the element that appears more than ⌊n / 2⌋ times. You may assume that the majority element always exists in the array.

 
Example 1:
Input: nums = [3,2,3]
Output: 3

Example 2:
Input: nums = [2,2,1,1,1,2,2]
Output: 2
 
Constraints:
n == nums.length
1 <= n <= 5 * 104
-109 <= nums[i] <= 109
The input is generated such that a majority element will exist in the array.
 
Follow-up: Could you solve the problem in linear time and in O(1) space?

Approach : Using Bayer Moore Voting Algorithm
          Step-by-Step Execution
          * Initialize: Start with a candidate (set to any value) and a count set to 0.
          * Iterate: Loop through every number in the array:
          * Check Count: If count is 0, assign the current number as the new candidate.
          * Update Count:
                  If the current number is the same as the candidate, increment count (+1).
                  If the current number is different, decrement count (-1).
          * Result: After one pass, the candidate is your majority element.

Why it works
Because the majority element occurs more than times, even if every other element "teams up" to decrement the count,
they don't have enough numbers to keep the majority element's count at zero by the end of the array.

Important Note
This algorithm assumes a majority element always exists as per the question given. 
//If it might not exist, you must do a second pass to count the occurrences of the final candidate and verify it exceeds.


Solution:
class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {
      //Using Bayer- Moore Voting Algorithm
      int count=0;
      int candidate=0;
      for(int num:nums){
        if(count==0){
            candidate=num;
        }
        count +=(num==candidate)? 1:-1;
      } 
      return candidate;
    }
}
